The United States (US) Extensions package provides the constructs needed to support its variations and extensions to the ICAO models.
This package builds upon the ISO 19100 family and the International Civil Aviation Organization's (ICAO) Aviation Meteorological eXchange Model (IWXXM).
The US METAR extensions are documented in Federal Meteorological Handbook No. 1 (FMH-1), Surface Weather Observations and Reports and Air Force Manual 15-111. US AIRMET, SIGMET and TAF variations and extensions are documented in the National Weather Service Instructions 10-811, 10-813, and Air Force Manual 15-124.

This package includes the information needed to model the Federal Aviation Administration's filed differences to the International Civil Aviation Organization for the METAR and SPECI products. Two US handbooks document observing practices and were used to guide the development of this package.
The Interagency Council for Advancing Meteorological Services (ICAMS) maintains the Federal Meteorological Handbook No. 1, Surface Weather Observations and Reports used primarily by the National Weather Service, the FAA and its contractors.
The Secretary of the US Air Force maintains the Air Force Manual 15-111, Surface Weather Observations for its airmen.
Complex types and enumerations shared among schemas.

This package includes the information needed to model the Federal Aviation Administration's filed differences to the International Civil Aviation Organization for the SIGMET product.
The National Weather Service Instruction 10-811 describes the content and preparation of its SIGMETs.

This package includes the information needed to model the Federal Aviation Administration's filed differences to the International Civil Aviation Organization for the AIRMET product.
The National Weather Service Instruction 10-811 describes the content and preparation of its AIRMETs.

This package includes the information needed to model the Federal Aviation Administration's filed differences to the International Civil Aviation Organization for the TAF products. Two publications were consulted while constructing this package. They are the National Weather Service Instruction 10-813, and Air Force Manual 15-124, Meteorological Codes.

This package includes the information needed to model the Federal Aviation Administration's filed differences to the International Civil Aviation Organization for the AIRMET product.
The National Weather Service Instruction 10-811 describes the content and preparation of its AIRMETs.
NWS Code List register of AIRMET weather hazards not listed in the WMO Registry.
Additional parameters in use by the NWS in issuing AIRMETs.
Time instant or period which the evolving condition is valid. This element shall have a value (or time period) that lies entirely within iwxxm:validPeriod.
Set of 0° Celsius isotherms denoting the 'shape' of the freezing levels in 3-D space.
Can be included in <extension> block within <AIRMETEvolvingCondition> elements, aka, polygons.

Weather phenomena not found in WMO Code Registry that is causing the hazard.
Boolean attribute/flag if weather phenomena is causing Low-Level Wind Shear conditions to occur.
Boolean attribute/flag if weather phenomena is causing:
1. Prevailing horizontal visibility reduced to less than 3 statute miles AND/OR 2. Broken or overcast cloud bases below 1000 feet (300 meters) AGL.
Boolean attribute/flag set to 'true' if weather phenomena is causing Low-Level Wind Shear conditions to occur.

Boolean attribute/flag set to 'true' if weather phenomena is causing:
  1. Prevailing horizontal visibility reduced to less than 3 statute miles AND/OR
  2. Broken or overcast cloud bases below 1000 feet (300 meters) AGL.
En route weather phenomena which may affect safety of flight and/or airport operations.
Depiction of 0° C isotherm at constant height, or flight level, above the ground.
Height of planar quasi-horizontal surface above mean sea level.
Sequence of geo-coordinates corresponding to the location of the 0° C isotherm on the quasi-horizontal plane that forms a closed loop.
Sequence of geo-coordinates corresponding to the location of the 0 degree isopleth on the quasi-horizontal plane that do not form a closed loop.
Pre-defined regions of Hawai'i and Alaska which forecast conditions are provided by NWS Aviation Services Units.
Set of 0° C isotherms at given forecast time period or instant.
Valid time period or instant of this freezing level forecast. The time references an instant in time or period that lies entirely within iwxxm:validPeriod.
Set of open and/or closed boundaries denoting areas of temperatures aloft that are at or below freezing.

This package includes the information needed to model the Federal Aviation Administration's filed differences to the International Civil Aviation Organization for the METAR and SPECI products. Two US handbooks document observing practices and were used to guide the development of this package.
The Interagency Council for Advancing Meteorological Services (ICAMS) maintains the Federal Meteorological Handbook No. 1, Surface Weather Observations and Reports used primarily by the National Weather Service, the FAA and its contractors.
The Secretary of the US Air Force maintains the Air Force Manual 15-111, Surface Weather Observations for its airmen.
At designated locations, and at 3- and 6-h intervals, the observer provides information on the predominate types of low-, middle- and high-level clouds at the time of the report.
Cloud type of the genera Stratocumulus, Stratus, Cumulus and Cumulonimbus.
Cloud type of the genera Altocumulus, Altostratus and Nimbostratus.
Cloud type of the genera Cirrus, Cirrocumulus and Cirrostratus.
The location and characteristics of observed lightning at the observation site.
Qualitative distance estimate from observation location to lightning activity, e.g, distant or in the vicinity.
Qualitative estimate of the number of lightning discharges within a 1 minute period.
Type(s) of lightning discharge activity observed at/surrounding the observation site.
One or more arcs which the lightning activity extends along the local horizon.
Measured flash frequency as determined by the observation system.
Weather phenomenon, either surface-based or aloft, that completely or partially obscure the sky.
Height of obscuring phenomenon above ground level. Value of zero indicates surface-based phenomenon.
Portion of the sky obscured by the phenomenon.
Weather phenomenon (surface-based or aloft) that completely or partially obscures the sky.
List of specialized equipment/sensors for recording or observing meteorological phenomena.
In situations of varying RVR, the mean value RVR distance for the runway shall be withheld and indicated with iwxxm:meanRVR attributes nilReason and xsi:nil set to withheld and true, respectively.
Visibility is less than sensor's minimum limits.
Visibility is greater than sensor's maximum limits.
Variable ceiling height shall be reported if height varies significantly during the sampling period of the report.
Minimum ceiling height observed during sampling period
Maximum ceiling height observed during sampling period

Where the observations occurs at aerodromes and ceiling and/or visibilities are monitored at second location, usually a runway, these parameters are reported when they are significantly lower than those reported at the usual observation location.
Lowest cloud base height of a broken or overcast cloud layer, if present.
If sensor determines that horizontal visibility is reduced below its ability to measure accurately, this attribute shall be present and set to 'true'.
Location of second set of ceiling and/or visibility sensors.

Aerodrome observation which ceiling and/or visibilities are monitored at second location, usually a runway, these parameters are reported when they are significantly lower than those reported at the usual (or standard) observation location.
Current list of inoperative sensors at the time of the report.
An observation system's sensor(s) which failed measurement standards and/or specifications at the time of the report.

A wind shift shall be indicated if a change in the wind direction of 45 degrees or more in less than 15 minutes with sustained wind speeds of 10 knots or more throughout the period occurs. Frontal passage may be indicated if it is reasonably certain that the wind shift was the result.
Set to true if its reasonably certain that the wind shift was caused by a frontal passage.
At designated stations whenever the snow depth increases by 1 in/h or more in the past hour, it shall be reported.
Measured increase in snow depth during the past hour.
At designated stations whenever the snow depth increases by 1 [in_i]/h or more in the past hour, it shall be reported.
List of commonly situated meteorological observation platforms.
Variable prevailing visibility shall be reported if criteria is met during the time of observation.
The lower bound value of the prevailing visibility during the sampling period.
The upper bound value of the prevailing visibility during the sampling period.
If minimum visibility is below sensor limitations or, for the human observer, the nearest reference point, this attribute shall be set to 'true'.
Sky cover shall be considered variable if it changes by one or more reportable values (few, scattered, broken, overcast) during the evaluation period.
The first of the operationally significant sky cover condition.
The second of the operationally significant sky cover condition.
This class shall refer to, via xlink:href, an external resource describing the geographical and/or technical specifications of the observation platform used to create the observation.
Reference to an external source that describes the technical and geographical specifications of the observation platform at the aerodrome.
Class containing meteorological conditions observed according to FMH-1 not already encoded in other IWXXM classes.
Observing system types in use by NWS and US Military

Plaintext which further elaborate on parameters reported in the body of the report, or contain information in an unstructured format and cannot be easily parsed. Examples include information on volcanic eruptions, funnel and rotor clouds, tornadoes, virga, aircraft mishaps, etc.

At designated stations, sea-level pressure shall be computed by adjusting the station pressure to compensate for the difference between the station elevation and sea-level. This adjustment shall be based on the station elevation and the 12-hour mean temperature at the station. The 12­hour mean temperature shall be the average of the present ambient temperature and the ambient temperature 12 hours ago.
Stations within ± 50 feet of sea-level may be authorized by their agency to use a constant value to adjust station pressure to sea-level pressure. Otherwise, stations shall use reduction ratios provided by their responsible agency to calculate sea-level pressure.

Designated stations shall include pressure tendency data in each 3- and 6-hourly report. The pressure tendency includes two parts: the characteristic (an indication of how the pressure has been changing over the past three hours) and the amount of the pressure change in the past three hours. The characteristic shall be based on the observed or recorded (barogram trace) changes in pressure over the past three hours. The amount of pressure change is the absolute value of the change in station pressure or altimeter setting in the past three hours converted to tenths of hectopascals.
Pressure tendency characteristic over the past 3 hours as described in the WMO Code Registry.

At designated stations, the pressure calculated for each report shall be examined to determine if a pressure change is occurring.
When the pressure is rising or falling rapidly at the time of observation, the remark PRESRR (pressure rising rapidly) or PRESFR (pressure falling rapidly) shall be included in the report.
Total snow depth on the ground if there is more than a trace on the ground.
True when condensation trails are observed in the past hour.
True when an aurora is observed in the past hour.
True when this report is the first one after a scheduled interruption.
True when this report is the last one before a scheduled interruption.
At manual stations where SPECI's are not taken, this shall set to 'true' to indicate that no changes in weather conditions will be reported until the next METAR.
The duration of sunshine that occurred the previous calendar day.
True when the automated system detects that maintenance is needed on the system.
Size of the largest hailstone found near the observation site
Supplementary data that cannot be automated. As such, these reports are taken manually, or augmented by a trained observer.
For suitably equipped observation platforms, the starting and ending times of precipitation/thunderstorm events are reported since the last issuance.

Statistically processed quantities in surface observation reports, such as maximum/minimum temperatures, precipitation amounts over a duration, etc. The processed value contains the actual measurement. The remaining attributes are needed to properly interpret the value.
The maximum instantaneous wind speed since the last observation that exceeded 25 knots and the time it occurred.
Wind direction of the peak gust.
This class contains additive data that cannot be automated. As such, these reports are taken manually, or augmented by a trained observer.
Reported tower visibility when controller cab visibility differs markedly from surface visibility and may affect airport operation.
Horizontal or slant visibility from the aerodrome air traffic control tower.
To indicate visibility less than the nearest visibility marker.
An enumeration of falling or rising.
A list of the 3-hourly pressure tendency groups.
List of convective cloud types which may affect the safety and navigability of aircraft surrounding the aerodrome.
At designated stations hailstone size (diameter) shall be reported in increments of 1/4 inch.
Hailstone size diameter in increments of 1/4 inch.
Hail less than 1/4 inch in size, this attribute shall be set to BELOW.
For suitably equipped observation platforms, the starting and ending times of precipitation/thunderstorm events are reported since the last issuance.
The starting (if known) and ending (if known) times of the precipitation/thunderstorm event.

At designated stations, maximum and minimum temperatures that occurred in the previous 6 hours shall be determined to the nearest tenth of a degree Celsius for the 0000, 0600, 1200, and 1800 UTC observations. The maximum and minimum temperatures for the previous 24 hours shall be determined to the nearest tenth of a degree Celsius for the 0000 LST observation.
The preceding time period which the extremes in air temperatures were observed.
Highest temperature that occurred during the preceding time period.
Lowest temperature that occurred during the preceding time period.
List of qualifiers for lightning frequency.
Refer to the corresponding context diagram to see its attributes.

This class supports a general need to capture statistically processed quantities in FMH-1 based surface observation reports, such as maximum/minimum temperatures, precipitation amounts over a duration, etc. The processed value contains the actual measurement. The remaining attributes are needed to properly interpret the value.
The meteorological parameter subjected to the statistical procedure.
Type of extreme value, e.g., minimum or maximum.
The time duration of the set of values which the statistical processing was applied.
If the measurement system specification(s) for the processed quantity is exceeded, i.e., ABOVE or BELOW.
The measured value of the meteorological parameter.
List of weather parameters that are statistically processed in the report.
Location of secondary suite of visibility and/or ceiling sensors. Candidate locations besides the airport reference point (ARP), are runways' touch down thresholds, midfield, alternate runways, etc.

Concise description of the secondary sensor location. Intended use is for further elucidation in conjunction with other attributes, e.g, 'Adjacent to runway touch down zone'. Or can be used by itself if the sensor's location cannot be indicated with the other attributes of this data type.
May appear in <iwxxm:METAR> or <iwxxm:SPECI> extension block
From designated or suitably equipped observation location, the distance to and subtended angle which thunderstorm, cumulonimbus or cumulomammatus clouds are observed.
Type of convective cloud being reported, e.g., thunderstorm, or cumulonimbus.
Qualitative distance estimate from observation location to convective activity, e.g, distant or in the vicinity.
One or more arcs which the convective cloud extends along the local horizon.
Direction which the convective cloud is moving towards in degrees from true north.
True if thunderstorm is moving overhead at the observing platform.
Endpoints of the azimuth angles and, optionally, measured distances to the phenomenon that defines the sector.
The counterclockwise-most extent of the observed convective cloud on the local horizon as expressed in degrees from true north.
Measured distance to the phenomena at the extreme counter-clockwise angle.
The clockwise-most extent of the observed convective cloud on the local horizon as expressed in degrees from true north.
Measured distance to the phenomena at the extreme clockwise angle.
If event is occurring in all quadrants of the horizon, this shall be set to true and no angles or distances provided.
Sector visibility shall be reported when it differs from the prevailing visibility by one or more reportable values and either the prevailing or sector visibility is less than 3 miles.
The sector's mid-point direction as expressed in degrees from true north.
If visibility in this sector is less than the nearest visual reference for distance or below sensors' minimum, this attribute shall be set to 'true'.
Type, and optionally, the location of the failed sensor(s).
The parameter that cannot be measured due to an inoperable sensor.
In case of multiple sensors of the same type at the aerodrome, location provides the position of the inoperable sensor.
For phenomena of, or associated with, a convective nature such as cumulonimbus clouds or lightning, a list of distance qualifiers.

This package includes the information needed to model the Federal Aviation Administration's filed differences to the International Civil Aviation Organization for the SIGMET product.
The National Weather Service Instruction 10-811 describes the content and preparation of its SIGMETs.
En route weather phenomena not in the WMO Registry which will affect safety of flight and/or airport operations.
En route weather phenomena which will affect safety of flight operations.
Forecaster free text regarding severe weather watch(es) affecting the SIGMET.
Expected or reported maximum wind speed gusts associated with convective activity.
Expected or reported maximum hail size diameter with convective activity.
Status regarding the presence of tornadic phenomena with convective activity.
Unique identifier of the hazardous region for tracking purposes.

This attribute is set 'true' if any of the following conditions are present: 1. Tornadic phenomenon, includes waterspouts 2. Hail size greater than or equal to 3/4 inches in diameter 3. Wind gusts exceeding 49 knots
Can be used in <extension> block within <SIGMET>, <SIGMETEvolvingCondition>, and <SIGMETPosition>
US specific hazards not found in WMO Code Registry which may affect the safety of aircraft operations.
List of states (by 2-letter Abbreviation) affected by the iwxxm:geometry.

This package includes the information needed to model the Federal Aviation Administration's filed differences to the International Civil Aviation Organization for the TAF products. Two publications were consulted while constructing this package. They are the National Weather Service Instruction 10-813, and Air Force Manual 15-124, Meteorological Codes.
AFMAN 15-124 Table 1.7 lists the allowable turbulence intensity and type.
May appear in the <iwxxm:TAF> extension element.

If observations, or human augmentation of the observations, are not available for a aerodrome, then TAFs issued for such stations will be governed by a special set of rules on when and how amendments will be issued.
List of weather parameters that can be amended.
Time period when amendments are restricted or unavailable.
Supplemental meteorological forecasting conditions at an aerodrome as needed by NWS and Air Force.
Forecasted lowest altimeter setting expected during the forecast period.
Forecast base and top of volcanic ash cloud (layer) above an aerodrome.
Forecast of expected direction of wind gusts.
Forecasted layers of turbulence above the aerodrome.

Low-level wind shear in the TAF will only refer to non-convective events and situations such as frontal passage, inversions, low-level wind jets, lee-side mountain flows, sea-breezes, Santa Ana winds, etc.
Wind direction at the top of the wind-shear layer.
Wind speed at the top of the wind shear layer.
Vertical extent of wind shear layer above/near the aerodrome.
List of meteorological parameters that will be monitored and updated with amendments.
Air Force Manual 15-124 on airframe icing intensity refer to WMO BUFR4 table.
Icing forecast for layer(s) above aerodrome.
Character and intensity of icing in layer.
Vertical extent of icing above aerodrome.
May appear in the <iwxxm:MeterologicalAerodromeForecast> extension element.
Forecasted type and severity of turbulence above the aerodrome.
Character and intensity of forecasted turbulence.
Vertical extent of turbulence above aerodrome.
Complex types and enumerations shared among schemas.

Describes the upper and lower limits of a layer above the aerodrome. This is needed for a number of weather elements, including non-convective low level wind shear, icing, turbulence, and volcanic ash.
Measured or estimated upper limit (height) of phenomenon.
Measured or estimated lower limit (height) of phenomenon.

RelationalOperator defines the restricted set of operators that may be specified alongside numerical quantities.
These operators are used in cases where a precise value is not measurable, not precisely known due to measurement limitations, or not reported due to reporting restrictions.
For example, the "BELOW" operator in conjunction with the reported quantity 1/4 indicates that the actual physical quantity is below 1/4 (at most 1/4).
The actual value is above the maximum value that can be determined by the system.
The actual value is below the minimum value that can be determined by the system.

Amount of cloud - assessed by category:
- Sky clear (0 oktas) - Few (1 - 2 oktas) - Scattered (3 - 4 oktas) - Broken (5 - 7 oktas) - Overcast (8 oktas)
This CodeList is specifically defined for aviation purposes, as defined in WMO No. 49-2. A superset of cloud-amount categories are defined in WMO No. 306 Vol I.2 FM 94 BUFR code-table 0 20 008 "Cloud distribution for aviation".
Additional information regarding the composition and generation of the observation and/or forecast product.
Reference to authoritative sources that governs and elucidates the process by which the meteorological observation or forecast is made.
Reference to documentation on the user-supplied aspects of the observation platform.
A nillable Length quantity. Unlike the base Length measure, references to this type may be nil and include a nilReason.
Free format text provided by the forecaster to provide additional information on the entire product or region(s) not encoded elsewhere.
Text entered by forecaster regarding any aspect of the SIGMET not already incorporated/included into the document.
A nillable Measure quantity. Unlike the base Measure, references to this type may be nil and may include a nilReason.

The present weather observed at, or in near vicinity of, an aerodrome.
Only a specific set of weather phenomenon are reported within aviation meteorology as defined in Regulation ICAO Annex 3 / WMO No. 49-2.
This CodeList is specifically defined for aviation purposes as defined in WMO No. 49-2. A superset of definitions are defined in WMO No. 306 Vol I.1 code-table 4678 "Significant weather phenomena".
